Feeding Instructions

WeightDaily Feeding (Cups)
3 - 12 lbs1/3 - 1
13 - 20 lbs1 - 1 1/3
21 - 35 lbs1/3 - 2
36 - 50 lbs2 - 2 1/2
51 - 75 lbs2 1/2 - 3 1/4
76 - 100 lbs3 1/4 - 4
Over 100 lbs4 + 1/4 cup for each 10 lbs over 100 lbs

We recommend that you keep your dog in ideal body condition and not allow your dog to become overweight. The exact amount of food your dog requires will need to be adjusted according to age, activity and environment. But a good place to start is with these guidelines for an average, active, adult dog fed once daily. Provide adequate fresh water in a clean container daily.

Transition Instructions

Please allow 7-10 days to ease the transition from your dog's current food. Each day, simply feed a little less of the previous food and a little more Pro Plan until you're feeding Pro Plan exclusively. This gradual transition will help avoid dietary upsets.

About Purina Pro Plan Sensitive Skin & Stomach

Purina Pro Plan Sensitive Skin & Stomach

Help nourish your dog’s sensitive systems and overall well-being with advanced nutrition to help him thrive. Pro Plan Sensitive Skin and Stomach dry formulas are made with real salmon, turkey or lamb as the #1 ingredient and omega-6 fatty acids for skin and coat health. Available in specialized formulas for adults, small breeds, large breeds, seniors and puppies and as a great-tasting wet formula.

With Rice or Oat Meal

These Pro Plan formulas are made with rice or oat meal, which are easily digestible and gentle on the GI system.

Protein & Fish Oil

High in protein and made with fish oil, a good source of EPA and DHA, for heart health.

Omega-6

Omega-6 fatty acids in Sensitive Skin & Stomach recipes help nourish the skin and coat.

Prebiotic Fiber

Natural prebiotic fiber in these formulas helps nourish specific intestinal bacteria for digestive health.

The Advanced Nutrition of Pro Plan

Always Advancing. Never Compromising. That’s Purina’s challenge to themselves, and their promise to you. They never stop researching, discovering, and enhancing the food your pet eats every day. Because for all they give to us, our pets deserve the world’s most advanced nutrition. Just ask the experts who trust it, the veterinarians who recommend it, and the champions who are fueled by it.

Questions & Answers

Terms & Conditions
68 Customer Questions
Is it true that the formula for purina pro plan salmon and rice for sensitive skin and stomach has changed? If so, why was the customer not notified?
Answer by Zach • Dec 24, 2023
Read the recent reviews, everyone seems to be.having issues me included. This caused my German shepherd to have uncontrollable diarrhea and this was the cause
is it ocean salmon or is it from a farm.
Answer by • Jun 30, 2018
Nestlé Purina PetCare Company utilizes both farm raised and ocean caught salmon in their products. Please know that Purina products are manufactured under strict quality control standards, and the safety and quality of their products are their top priorities.
What is the Ash content of this food?
Answer by • Oct 26, 2018
This recipe contains 7.6% Ash content, on an as fed basis.
why is there no taurine listed in ingredients?
Answer by • Nov 30, 2019
This formula does not contain synthetically added taurine. Taurine is found naturally within meat, with the level varying depending on the type of meat. This formula has a taurine content of 0.12% on an as fed basis.

Rated 1 out of 5 stars
By Young on Mar 12, 2024

My Dogs Hated it

Neither of my dogs (45lb Jindo/Akita and 25lb Dalmation/Maltese) could "stomach" this "sensitive stomach" food.  As I added it gradually to their old food (Hills Science Diet) to make the switch, they started to pick around it and would leave nearly all of it in the bowl.  When I finally switched over to this exclusively, they refused to eat it at first but then finally gave in.  Almost immediately, they both got sick and threw up everything they ate.  I attributed it to changing their food so started to mix in some wet food, boiled chicken breast, and lean beef to incentivize them to eat.  They picked around the food and only ate the chicken or beef.  They used to be happy with just the dry food and some "extras" 2 or 3 times a week and would dive right in.  When I put this in their bowl, they just sat and looked at me like I was trying to poison them.

Rated 1 out of 5 stars
By Madeline on Mar 31, 2024

Formula change - food refusal

Unfortunately Purina changed their formula a few months ago without informing consumers. Our dog has been refusing the food and eating a lot less of it when he does eat. In a recent bag, there were random pieces of a red, different shaped kibble which was concerning. They also removed the probiotics in the formula which led to looser stools. Very disappointed in Purina, but Chewy provided great customer service and refunded us for our recent bag.

Rated 4 out of 5 stars
By Jennifer on Mar 11, 2024

No Issues

My dog has been on this food for many years now and has not shown any signs or symptoms that I am reading on other reviews. I even purchased a bag in December, which she is now finishing and she has had no issues. I also visited Purina Pro Plan's website and they are addressing all of these recent complaints and taking it seriously and I trust they are going to do what is right if they in fact find issues. Furthermore, all of these reviews can cause pet owners like me to go down a rabbit hole trying to find another brand to feed my loving dogs and that alone is another task at hand because most people leave a review just to complain. So, for right now, I am keeping my dog on this brand until she is considered a senior later this year.

Rated 1 out of 5 stars
By Lauren on Mar 10, 2024

Recipe Changed

My 3 year old labradoodle had been eating this for 1.5 years with no issues. He was never excited about mealtime, but we just figured he was a grazer. Last November, he started throwing up a few times a week and we tried everything except changing his food, but nothing worked. We figured since this food is for sensitive stomachs, that couldn’t be it. Finally in early January we switched to Beneful, and things got worse- he started throwing up AND diarrhea. We switched completely to another smaller, more natural food brand and he is now excited for meal time and the gastro issues stopped immediately. From reading other reviews, it seems that Purina changed their recipe around last November and a lot of doggos are having issues with the new recipe. Just be aware of this if your dog has any issues while eating this brand!

Rated 1 out of 5 stars
By Amanda on Mar 8, 2024

Incredibly Ill

I had been feeding my dog purina pro plan sensitive stomach since she was roughly 4 months old. It was such a blessing to find a dog food that helped her with her stomach issues. I had never had any issues until Christmas Eve when we got a new bag. Within hours my sweet, loving, playful 3 year old dog would not walk and became severely lethargic. I instantly gave her pumpkin and rice to help her tummy issues and attempted to contact her vet. We agreed to give her a pumpkin and rice mixture for 24 hours. She got better the next day and on Christmas night I gave her another serving of her food and experienced the same exact symptoms once again, within hours! Extremely lethargic, wouldn’t move, curled up in my lap. It was her way of screaming out to me that she was literally being poisoned. I then looked up this dog food only to see she is not the only one. I IMMEDIATELY bagged her food up to discard and knew she would NEVER eat this food again. Such a shame that this company is getting away with poisoning our puppies. I am beyond blessed that we picked up on her ques right away and did not have a different outcome that far too many others experienced. After multiple trips to the vet and over $1000 for medicines and prescription dog food she is in the clear.

Purina is compliant with WSAVA guidelines. I have not had a dog get sick from this food once since we started it in 2018.

Rated 2 out of 5 stars
By Michelle on Feb 29, 2024

Change in Formula?

My boy has been eating Sensitive Skin & Stomach Salmon & Rice for quite a while now with no problems. It helped clear his head shaking and gland issues. Something changed with this last bag. He started having horrible gas, his stomach started grumbling, and he had intermittent vomiting. I took him to the vet and he was put on a bland diet, probiotics, stomach meds and Prilosec. He started getting better so we started adding the food back in. Right away, the stomach issues started again. Two days ago he stopped eating altogether. After reading reviews here, I bought the turkey and rice formula and he gobbled it down. No stomach issues since. I don't know what's changed, but I won't risk putting him through that misery again.
